property.name: text
property.value: General Model Description: This model shows a intersection between four roads controlled by one traffic lights for each road. The crossing actor has a sensor that measures type, speed and distance of an vehicle. A distinction is made between autonomous cars and human-driven cars. If the sensor only perceives autonomous cars, all traffic lights are switched to green, otherwise the crossing actor takes over the traffic light control. The Poisson Clock generates a new vehicle with a certain speed.

property.name: text
property.value:
CarType := 0 -> Human Driven ; 1 -> Autonomous
CarDirection := 0 -> straight ; 1 -> turnRight ; 2 -> turnLeft

property.name: text
property.value:
The model is separated in 2 steps. The first is determining the intersection phases, which is primarily done in the first Compostite Actor (TLController). The second is putting cars in a queue and, depending on their direction (blinker) determine which one is going first. This is done in the second Composite Actor (RightOfWay) which takes the TLs from the previous one as inputs.
Sadly, this part from our model stops after the first 4 periods. Nevertheless, the traffic lights periods continue until the end.

property.name: text
property.value: The cars are queued roadwise. When the traffic light for one road is green, the first cars on each side are free to enter the intersection. The finite state machine right after the queues determines which car can go first, depending on their direction. If both are going straight or turning right (or left), everything is fine and they can go simultanuously. If one of them is turning left, he needs to wait for 5 seconds, as he wants to cross the counterparts street.
